The paper discusses computer vision and machine learning techniques applied to robotic assisted surgery, which suggests that it could belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) or robotics (cs.RO) sub-categories. The use of public datasets and benchmarking methods also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of deep learning techniques, which further supports the possibility of it belonging to the computer vision or machine learning sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves segmentation of robotic instruments, which could potentially fall under the multimedia (cs.MM) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories.
